post_cb({"35377671": {"CommentCount": "2", "ViewCount": "35", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "2877241", "CreationDate": "2016-02-13T08:17:54.920", "LastActivityDate": "2016-02-14T04:57:43.480", "Title": "Memory allocation using array", "AcceptedAnswerId": "35377708", "LastEditDate": "2016-02-13T08:23:38.027", "Id": "35377671", "Score": "-4", "Body": "<p>Can someone please tell me, what in general, will the following do in C ?</p>\n<pre><code>H.L = new int* [H.n];\n</code></pre>\n<p>Does this command create L variable in structure H of integer type with size n?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><pointers><structure>", "OwnerUserId": "5921722", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "35377708": {"ParentId": "35377671", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>It will create an array of <code>H.n</code> pointers to <code>int</code>. A pointer to the first array element will be stored in <code>H.L</code>. </p>\n<p>If you wanted an array of <code>int</code>s, remove the asterisk. </p>\n<p>On a side note, you may be happier using a <code>vector&lt;int*&gt;</code> instead.</p>\n<p>It is much easier to use.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "4566726", "LastEditorUserId": "5463883", "LastEditDate": "2016-02-14T04:57:43.480", "Id": "35377708", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2016-02-13T08:22:36.447", "LastActivityDate": "2016-02-14T04:57:43.480"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_35377671_35377775_0": {"section_id": 6082, "quality": 1.0, "length": 7}}, "n3337": {"so_35377671_35377775_0": {"section_id": 5850, "quality": 1.0, "length": 7}}, "n4659": {"so_35377671_35377775_0": {"section_id": 7578, "quality": 1.0, "length": 7}}}, "35377775": {"ParentId": "35377671", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>In the right side of the expression statement</p>\n<pre><code>H.L = new int* [H.n];\n</code></pre>\n<p>there is created an array of type <code>int *[H.n]</code> using unary operator <code>new []</code>. That is each element of the array has type <code>int *</code>. </p>\n<p>Expression <code>H.n</code> used in square brackets specifies the number of elements of the allocated array and must be converted to type <code>size_t</code>. Usually it is some integral type as for example <code>int</code>.</p>\n<p>According to the C+ Standard (5.3.4 New)</p>\n<blockquote id=\"so_35377671_35377775_0\">\n<ol>\n<li>...If it is an array, the new-expression returns a pointer to the initial\n  element of the array.</li>\n</ol>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So the left side lvalue <code>H.L</code> should have type <code>int **</code> or some type (usually in rare cases) that can be converted from <code>int **</code>.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "2877241", "LastEditorUserId": "2877241", "LastEditDate": "2016-02-13T08:37:00.797", "Id": "35377775", "Score": "0", "CreationDate": "2016-02-13T08:31:56.073", "LastActivityDate": "2016-02-13T08:37:00.797"}});